*{{IPA|/m, p, b, β/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=219}}
*The word-initial {{IPA|/sx/}} cluster can be realized as {{IPA|[ɕx]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=220}}
*{{IPA|/ʃ, ʒ/}} do not occur as frequently as in many other dialects, and can be said to be marginal phonemes.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=220}}
*{{IPA|/ŋ, k, x, ɣ/}} are [[Velar consonant|velar]], whereas {{IPA|/j/}} is [[Palatal consonant|palatal]].{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=219}}
*{{IPA|/ʀ/}} is a [[uvular trill]]. Word-finally it is devoiced to either a fricative {{IPAblink|χ}} or a trill fricative {{IPAblink|ʀ̝̊}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|pp=220–221}}
*Other allophones include {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɱ}}, {{IPA link|ɲ}}, {{IPA link|c}}, {{IPA link|ɡ}}]}}. They appear in contexts similar to Belgian Standard Dutch.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=220}}
*Voiceless consonants are regressively [[Assimilation (linguistics)|assimilated]]. An example of this is the past tense of regular verbs, where voiceless stops and fricatives are voiced before the past tense morpheme {{IPA|[də]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=220}}
*Word-final voiceless consonants are voiced in intervocalic position.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=220}}

===Vowels===
The Hamont dialect contains 22 monophthong and 13 diphthong phonemes.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}} The amount of monophthongs is higher than that of consonants.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}

====Monophthongs====
[[Image:Hamont Limburgish monophthong chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Monophthong]]s of the Hamont dialect, from {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}]]
