! [[Stress (linguistics)|Unstressable]]
| colspan="6" | {{IPA link|ə}}
|}


On average, long vowels are 95 ms longer than short vowels. This is very similar to Belgian Standard Dutch, in which the difference is 105 ms.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=220}}{{sfnp|Verhoeven|Van Bael|2002}}

The quality of the monophthongs is as follows:
* {{IPA|/i, iː, yː, u, uː, eː, øː, oː, ɛ, ɛː, œ, œː, ɔ, ɔː, ɑː/}} are similar to the corresponding cardinal vowels {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|y}}, {{IPA link|u}}, {{IPA link|e}}, {{IPA link|ø}}, {{IPA link|o}}, {{IPA link|ɛ}}, {{IPA link|œ}}, {{IPA link|ɔ}}, {{IPA link|ɑ}}]}}, but none of them are quite as peripheral.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* {{IPA|/y/}} is [[mid-centralized]] in relation to the long {{IPA|/yː/}} (this is not shown on the vowel chart). It can be described as near-close advanced central {{IPAblink|ʉ̞|ʉ̞˖}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|pp=221, 223}}
* {{IPA|/ɪ/}} is similar to {{IPA|/eː/}}, but it is lower and slightly more central ({{IPAblink|ɪ|ɪ̞}}). For some speakers there is additional non-phonemic long {{IPAblink|ɪː}}, which can appear in words such as ''noordenw'''i'''nd'' {{IPA|[ˈnoːʀdəʀβɪːnt]}} ('north wind'). This is probably an influence of Belgian Standard Dutch.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|pp=221, 224}}
* {{IPA|/ʏ/}}, a phonological front vowel, is phonetically central {{IPAblink|ɵ}}. As in Standard Dutch, it can be considered to be a stressed equivalent of {{IPA|/ə/}} as they differ mainly in rounding.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|pp=220–221}}
* The contrast between the long open vowels is a genuine front–central–back contrast. The Hamont dialect thus has four, not five phonemic vowel heights.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|pp=221–222}}
* {{IPA|/æː/}} is open front {{IPAblink|æ̞ː}}, whereas {{IPA|/aː/}} is open central {{IPAblink|äː}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The short {{IPA|/æ/}} and {{IPA|/ɑ/}} are somewhat higher and more front ({{IPA|[{{IPA link|æ}}, {{IPA link|ɑ|ɑ̝̈}}]}}) than their long counterparts. This is not shown on the vowel chart.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}

====Monophthong-glide combinations====

All monophthong-glide combinations are restricted to the [[Syllable#Coda|syllable coda]].{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=222}}

====Diphthongs====
Dialect of Hamont contrasts long and short closing diphthongs. The long ones are on average 70 ms longer than their short equivalents. Centering diphthongs are all long.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}

[[Image:Hamont Limburgish diphthong chart (closing).svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Closing [[diphthong]]s of the Hamont dialect, from {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}]]
[[Image:Hamont Limburgish diphthong chart (centering).svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Centering diphthongs of the Hamont dialect, from {{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}]]

{| class="wikitable" style="margin: auto; text-align: center;"
|+ [[Diphthong]] phonemes{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|pp=221–222}}
|-
! rowspan="2" | Closing
! {{small|short}}
| {{IPA|ɛi œy ɔu ɑu}}
|-
! {{small|long}}
| {{IPA|ɛiː œyː ɔuː ɑuː}}
|-
! colspan="2" | Centering
| {{IPA|iːə yːə uːə oːə ɔːə}}
|}

* The starting points of {{IPA|/ɛi(ː), œy(ː)/}} are close to the corresponding cardinal vowels {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɛ}}, {{IPA link|œ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The starting point of {{IPA|/ɑu(ː)/}} is near-open central {{IPAblink|ɐ}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The ending points of {{IPA|/ɛi(ː), œy(ː), ɔu(ː)/}} are rather close, more like {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|y}}, {{IPA link|u}}]}} than {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʏ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The ending point of {{IPA|/ɑu(ː)/}} is slightly more open ({{IPAblink|ʊ}}) than those of the other closing diphthongs.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The starting points of {{IPA|/ɔu(ː)/}} and {{IPA|/oːə/}} are more central than the corresponding cardinal vowels: {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɔ|ɔ̟}}, {{IPA link|o|o̟}}]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The starting points of {{IPA|/iːə, yːə/}} are somewhat lower ({{IPA|[{{IPA link|i|i̞}}, {{IPA link|y|y˕}}]}}) than the corresponding cardinal vowels.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The starting point of {{IPA|/uːə/}} is somewhat lower and somewhat more central ({{IPAblink|u|ü̞}}) than the corresponding cardinal vowel.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}
* The starting point of {{IPA|/ɔːə/}} is somewhat higher and somewhat more central ({{IPAblink|ɔ|ɔ̝̈}}) than the corresponding cardinal vowel.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=221}}

===Prosody===
Like most other Limburgish dialects, but unlike some other dialects in this area,{{sfnp|Schouten|Peeters|1996}}{{sfnp|Heijmans|Gussenhoven|1998|p=111}} the prosody of the Hamont dialect has a lexical tone distinction, which is traditionally referred to as ''stoottoon'' ('push tone') or ''Accent 1'' and ''sleeptoon'' ('dragging tone') or ''Accent 2''. They are transcribed as superscript 1 and superscript 2, respectively. This distinction can signal either lexical differences or grammatical distinctions, such as those between the singular and the plural forms of some nouns.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=223}}

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
|+ Examples{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=223}}
! colspan="2" | Accent 1
! colspan="2" | Accent 2
|-
! IPA
! Meaning
! IPA
! Meaning
|-
| {{IPA|/ɦus¹/}}
| '(record) sleeve'
| {{IPA|/ɦus²/}}
| 'house'
|-
| {{IPA|/kəˈnin¹/}}
| 'rabbits'
| {{IPA|/kəˈniːn²/}}
| 'rabbit'
|-
| {{IPA|/tiːən¹/}}
| 'toes'
| {{IPA|/tiːən²/}}
| 'toe'
|}

The distinction between Accent 1 and Accent 2 is phonemic only in stressed syllables.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=223}}

In final position, Accent 1 is realised as a steady fall {{IPA|[V˥˩]}} through the rhyme, the Accent 2 is falling-rising {{IPA|[V˥˩˩˥]}}; the first half of the rhyme is falling, whereas the rest is rising.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=223}}

In non-final position, Accent 1's F0 stays high in the first 45% of the rhyme and then falls rapidly towards the end of the rhyme (in IPA, that can be transcribed {{IPA|[V˦˥]}}). When the focus of the sentence is on a word with Accent 2, it is realized as a very shallow fall-rise combination {{IPA|[V˥˩˩˥]}}.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=224}}

Vowels with Accent 1 are generally shorter than those with Accent 2.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=224}}

===Sample===
The sample text is a reading of the first sentence of [[The North Wind and the Sun]], read by a 75-year-old male middle-class speaker.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=219}}

====Phonetic transcription====
{{IPA|[də noːʀdəʀβ̞ɪːnd ɛn də zɔn {{!}} di β̞ɑʀə ʀyzi n̩t maːkə ʔoːvəʀ β̞i t̩ stɛʀkstə β̞ɑs {{!}} tun əʀənə vɛ̃ːnt fəʀbɛiː kβ̞ɑːmp mɛ nə β̞ɛʀmə jɑz ɔːn]}}<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Verhoeven|2007|pp=224–225}}. Note that the author transcribes ''de'' as *{{IPA|[de]}}, rather than the correct {{IPA|[də]}}.</ref>

====Orthographic version (Standard Belgian Dutch)====
De noordenwind en de zon waren ruzie aan het maken over wie het sterkste was toen er een man voorbij kwam met een warme jas aan.{{sfnp|Verhoeven|2007|p=225}}

