'''[[Lesotho]]''', a [[country]] in [[Southern Africa]], is home to several '''languages''', including [[Phuthi language|Phuthi]], [[Sesotho language|Sesotho]], [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]], [[Zulu language|Zulu]] and [[English language|English]], — all, except for English, belong to the [[Niger–Congo languages|Niger–Congo]] [[language family]].<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica">{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]] |title=Lesotho |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/337126/Lesotho |accessdate=3 October 2010 |year=2010}}</ref>

== National and official languages ==

[[Sesotho language|Sesotho]] (or Southern Sesotho), a [[Southern Bantu languages|Southern Bantu]] language, is the [[national language]] of Lesotho,<ref>{{Harvnb|Dalby|2004|p=576}}.</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Deprez|Du Plessis|Teck|2001|p=175}}.</ref><ref group="note">The name "Lesotho" translates roughly as "the land of the people who speak Sesotho", Sesotho meaning "the Sesotho language"; see {{Harvnb|Itano|2007|p=314}}.</ref> and is spoken by most [[Basotho]].<ref group="note">The people of Lesotho are called Basotho (sing. Mosotho), where "ba-" indicates plural; see {{Harvnb|Rosenberg|Weisfelder|Frisbie-Fulton|2005|p=12}} and {{Harvnb|Van Wyk|1998|p=54}}.</ref>  It was recognized as the national language by the National and Official Languages Bill, ratified by the [[National Assembly of Lesotho]] on 12 September 1966, which also established Sesotho and English as the country's two [[official language]]s.<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica"/><ref>{{Harvnb|Rosenberg|Weisfelder|Frisbie-Fulton|2005|p=319}}.</ref>  The country's [[language policy]] promotes [[bilingualism]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Legère|Fitchat|Akindele|2002|p=109}}.</ref> and Chapter 1 of the Constitution of Lesotho states:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aceproject.org/ero-en/regions/africa/LS/Constitution%20of%20Lesotho%201993.pdf |title=The Constitution of Lesotho |year=1993 |work=ACE Electoral Knowledge Network |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate=6 October 2010}}</ref>
{{quote|text=The official languages of Lesotho shall be Sesotho and English and, accordingly, no instrument or transaction shall be invalid by reason only that it is expressed or conducted in one of those languages.|source=The Constitution of Lesotho, 1993}}

Sesotho is the [[first language]] of more than 90 percent of the population<ref>{{Harvnb|Baker|Prys Jones|1998|p=270}}.</ref> and is "used widely as a medium of communication" in day-to-day speech.<ref name="Baker & Prys Jones 1998: 315">{{Harvnb|Baker|Prys Jones|1998|p=315}}.</ref>  English is reserved for official interactions,<ref name="Baker & Prys Jones 1998: 315"/> such as "government and administration",<ref name="Baker & Prys Jones 1998: 361">{{Harvnb|Baker|Prys Jones|1998|p=361}}.</ref> although the use of Sesotho in politics, religion, and the mass media is growing.<ref>{{Harvnb|Baker|Prys Jones|1998|pp=270, 361}}.</ref>

[[Primary education]] of children takes place in Sesotho for the first four years, but English becomes the [[medium of instruction]] in the fifth year of [[primary school]].<ref name="Baker & Prys Jones 1998: 361"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lesothotokyo.org/en/basic_data/index.html |title=Basic Facts |work=The Embassy of the Kingdom of Lesotho – Tokyo, Japan |accessdate=3 October 2010}}</ref>  Competence in English is "particularly important ... for educational, political, social and economic transactions in the subcontinent"<ref>{{Harvnb|Legère|Fitchat|Akindele|2002|p=114}}.</ref> and facilitates obtaining employment within Lesotho and abroad.<ref name="Webb 1995: 96">{{Harvnb|Webb|1995|p=96}}.</ref>  Although "efforts are made to ensure that Basotho children" learn to read, speak and write English,<ref name="Webb 1995: 96"/> many Basotho complete only "basic primary education [and] remain monolingual in Sesotho".<ref name="Baker & Prys Jones 1998: 361"/>

== Minority and immigrant languages ==

A minority of Basotho, estimated to number 248,000 {{as of|1993|lc=on}}, speak [[Zulu language|Zulu]], one of the eleven official languages of [[South Africa]].<ref name="Ethnologue (16th ed): Lesotho">{{Harvnb|Lewis|2009}}, [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=lesotho Lesotho] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041915/http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=Lesotho |date=2011-07-04 }} at [[Ethnologue]]. Retrieved 3 October 2010.</ref>  [[Phuthi language|Phuthi]], a [[Nguni languages|Nguni language]] closely related to [[Swazi language|Swazi]], an official language of South Africa and [[Swaziland]], is spoken by 43,000 Basotho ({{as of|2002|lc=on}}).<ref name="Ethnologue (16th ed): Lesotho"/>  [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]], another Nguni language and official language of South Africa, is spoken by 18,000 people in Lesotho.<ref name="Ethnologue (16th ed): Lesotho"/>  Speakers of these [[minority language]]s typically also speak Sotho.<ref name="Baker & Prys Jones 1998: 361"/>

[[Afrikaans]], spoken mainly in South Africa and [[Namibia]], is an [[immigrant language]].<ref name="Ethnologue (16th ed): Lesotho"/>

